{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-acfbd5de93da3562", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\tSelf-supervised Speech Comparison for\n2\tL2 Phone, Rhythm, and Intonation Scoring\n3\tStephen McIntosh†∗ , Reuben Smit‡∗ , Daisuke Saito† , Nobuaki Minematsu† and Herman Kamper‡\n4\t† The University of Tokyo, Japan\n5\t\n6\t‡ Stellenbosch University, South Africa\n7\t\n8\tarXiv:2607.13721v1 [cs.CL] 15 Jul 2026\n9\t\n10\t{smcintosh, dsk saito, mine}@gavo.t.u-tokyo.ac.jp\n11\t\n12\tAbstract—L2 speech assessment has traditionally focused on\n13\tphonetic assessment, leaving the scoring of suprasegmental\n14\tfeatures such as rhythm and intonation underexplored. Moreover,\n15\tassessment methods often require training with labeled L2\n16\tspeech data, making them difficult to apply in low-resource\n17\tsettings. We investigate whether DTW over self-supervised\n18\tWavLM representations can provide a text-free framework for\n19\tassessing phonetic accuracy, rhythm, and intonation in English\n20\tand Japanese L2 speech. Results show that a basic DTW-based\n21\tapproach that compares learner speech to native templates exceeds\n22\thuman agreement on holistic and sentence-level phonetic scoring.\n23\tFor rhythm, we introduce methods that measure the degree of\n24\twarping in the DTW alignment path; our best method approaches\n25\thuman-level performance. For intonation, we combine DTW\n26\tdistance over prosodic residuals with pitch and intensity features,\n27\tbut performance remains more modest on some tasks. Our results\n28\tpoint to self-supervised representations as a promising, text-free\n29\tbasis for multi-aspect pronunciation assessment.\n30\tIndex Terms—automatic pronunciation assessment, selfsupervised speech models, second-language learning\n31\t\n32\tI. I NTRODUCTION\n33\tMost work in automatic second-language (L2) speech\n34\tevaluation focuses on segmental features (i.e., phones), disregarding suprasegmental (prosodic) features such as rhythm and\n35\tintonation [1]. However, suprasegmental aspects of speech play\n36\ta vital role in how listeners process and understand spoken\n37\tlanguage [2]–[4]. Skilled expression of these speech aspects is\n38\tknown to improve comprehensibility and reduce accentedness\n39\tof L2 speech [5]–[7].\n40\tIn this work, we predict phonetic and prosody scores\n41\tof L2 utterances by comparing their self-supervised speech\n42\trepresentations to those of native speech templates. Our\n43\tmethods only use a few native templates of the target content\n44\tand are therefore viable for L2 assessment in low-resource\n45\tlanguages where gathering scored L2 speech is challenging. Our\n46\tapproach is summarized in Figure 1: We align self-supervised\n47\tspeech representations of native templates with L2 learner\n48\tspeech using dynamic time warping (DTW). We use this\n49\talignment in various comparison methods, each of which targets\n50\tphonetics, rhythm, or intonation. We then average the raw\n51\tresults of these methods over all native references into one\n52\trepresentative comparison score. To evaluate each method, we\n53\tcalculate the correlations of these aggregate scores with human\n54\tratings, and compare with pairwise human agreement.\n55\t∗ These authors contributed equally.\n56\t\n57\t{28583272, kamperh}@sun.ac.za\n58\t\n59\tIn experiments on English and Japanese, we demonstrate that\n60\tself-supervised speech representations combined with DTW\n61\tprovide useful information for automated pronunciation scoring.\n62\tFor phonetic assessment, they perform well and sometimes\n63\texceed expert inter-rater agreement. For rhythm, we show that\n64\tthe warping path itself is a rich source of information: our two\n65\tnovel rhythm metrics approach human inter-rater agreement,\n66\twhile significantly outperforming the conventional baseline.\n67\tWe introduce k-means residuals of SSL features as a prosodic\n68\tsignal for intonation scoring, and show that they outperform F0\n69\tand intensity features, although overall performance is modest\n70\twhen compared to human experts.\n71\tOur primary contribution is the introduction of novel DTWbased approaches for assessing suprasegmental speech aspects\n72\tin L2 speech. To our knowledge, we also provide the first comparison of template-based assessment methods to inter-human\n73\tagreement for both segmentals and suprasegmentals. Upon\n74\tacceptance, we will release our methods and evaluation code.\n75\t\n76\tL2 learner\n77\t\n78\tSSL features\n79\t\n80\tComparison methods\n81\tIndividual/Ensemble\n82\tPhonetic\n83\tDTW\n84\t\n85\tNative speakers\n86\t\n87\tRhythm\n88\t\n89\tShorter\n90\t\n91\tPhonetic difference\n92\t\n93\tLonger\n94\t\n95\tLonger\n96\t\n97\tRhythmic\n98\tdifference\n99\tIntonation\n100\t\n101\tScores per reference\n102\tSegmental\n103\tRhythm\n104\tIntonation\n105\t\n106\tMore\n107\tsimilar\n108\t\n109\tLess\n110\tsimilar\n111\t\n112\tAveraged score\n113\tSegmental\n114\t\n115\tMore\n116\tsimilar\n117\t\n118\tLess\n119\tsimilar\n120\t\n121\tRhythm\n122\tIntonation\n123\t\n124\tFig. 1. Our L2 pronunciation assessment approach. Self-supervised speech\n125\trepresentations from second-language learners are compared with native\n126\treferences to identify differences in phones, rhythm, and intonation. The\n127\traw scores are then converted to ordinal scores.\n128\t\n129\t\fII. R ELATED W ORK\n130\t\n131\tsay, prosody (the suprasegmentals) pertains to how you say it.\n132\tWe further split prosody into intonation and rhythm.\n133\tAutomatic pronunciation assessment has been a core comAs seen in Figure 1, our methods compare learner speech to\n134\tponent of computer-assisted pronunciation systems for several\n135\ta native template using DTW alignment of WavLM-Large [24]\n136\tdecades. It has broadly fallen into two paradigms: acousticrepresentations. We define the distance between two frames by\n137\tmodel-based approaches, and template-b