6\tbreakdowns in Tables II and III.\n507\tTo understand which features drive ensemble performance,\n508\twe also apply a Shapley-based attribution framework to each\n509\tensemble model [42]. Shapley values decompose the model’s\n510\tTABLE II\n511\texplained variance additively across input features, providing\n512\tE VALUATION RESULTS FOR TASKS IN THE ERJ [40] DATASET (E NGLISH )\n513\ta principled measure of each feature’s marginal contribution.\n514\tV. R ESULTS\n515\tWe first look at the overall best results before turning to\n516\ta detailed analysis. For all assessed tasks, our DTW-based\n517\tmethods comfortably outperform the baselines and largely\n518\tapproach human agreement.\n519\tEvaluation results for the best method on each task are\n520\tsummarized in Figure 5. SSL-based methods perform well\n521\toverall, most strikingly for phonetic scoring of sentences,\n522\twhere DTW over SSL features significantly exceeds human\n523\tinter-rater agreement. Phonetic scoring of isolated words is\n524\tweaker, consistent with the reduced averaging and alignment\n525\tconstraints that short sequences impose on DTW-based methods.\n526\tFor tasks with a rhythmic component (i.e., English sentence\n527\trhythm and English word accent), our methods fall only slightly\n528\t\n529\tERJ (English)\n530\t\n531\tr (↑)\n532\t\n533\tρ (↑) QWK (↑) MAE (↓)\n534\t\n535\tPhones (sentence)\n536\tHuman benchmark\n537\t\n538\t53.6\n539\t\n540\t51.5\n541\t\n542\t49.1\n543\t\n544\t0.75\n545\t\n546\t57.6\n547\t36.9\n548\t\n549\t55.8\n550\t36.5\n551\t\n552\t44.7\n553\t18.3\n554\t\n555\t0.64\n556\t0.72\n557\t\n558\t49.3\n559\t\n560\t48.2\n561\t\n562\t45.9\n563\t\n564\t0.81\n565\t\n566\t44.9\n567\t43.6\n568\t43.5\n569\t37.3\n570\t31.7\n571\t16.5\n572\t\n573\t45.8\n574\t44.9\n575\t44.2\n576\t39.0\n577\t30.3\n578\t16.5\n579\t\n580\t33.8\n581\t31.3\n582\t32.4\n583\t25.9\n584\t21.8\n585\t10.2\n586\t\n587\t0.73\n588\t0.74\n589\t0.73\n590\t0.76\n591\t0.78\n592\t0.84\n593\t\n594\t45.3\n595\t\n596