y (baseline)\n730\t\n731\t∗ Ensemble method. Bold: best or statistically equivalent (speaker-cluster\n732\tbootstrap, p > 0.05). † Significantly exceeds the human benchmark (p < 0.05).\n733\t\n734\t\fA. ERJ (English)\n735\tPhones: For phonetic scoring of sentences, standard DTW\n736\tdistance on SSL features (r = 57.6) alone significantly exceeds\n737\thuman agreement (r = 53.6). However, the results are worse\n738\tfor the phonetic scoring of words, which is understandable, as\n739\tSSL models rely on context in a longer utterance to improve\n740\tthe quality of representations.\n741\tSentence rhythm: The best-performing rhythm model\n742\tcombines Rdur and interval distortion (r = 44.9, the highest\n743\tamong suprasegmental tasks), though interval distortion alone\n744\t(r = 43.6) is statistically indistinguishable from it. These are\n745\tclose because interval distortion already encodes speech rate\n746\t(Pearson correlation is 0.44 with Rdur ), so the inclusion of\n747\tduration does not contribute much (28.8% of the ensemble’s\n748\texplained variance). In contrast, tempo irregularity is nearly\n749\trate-invariant (0.24 correlation with Rdur ), so it benefits more\n750\tfrom ensembling with duration (which is responsible for 40.3%\n751\tof the explained variance). All of the best methods incorporate\n752\tboth global speaking rate and local timing information, consistent with findings that more proficient speakers speak more\n753\tquickly and have more appropriate local rhythm [43].\n754\tIntonation: Our best-performing intonation method achieves\n755\tr = 32.9 (human benchmark r = 45.3), among the lowest of all\n756\tevaluated tasks. Shapley attribution indicates that DTWL6\n757\tnorm. res\n758\tis the dominant contributor (41.0%), followed by F0 –intensity\n759\tL6\n760\tfeatures (31.2%) and σres\n761\t(27.8%). Despite achieving a lower\n762\tMAE than the human benchmark (0.87 vs. 0.98), the correlation\n763\tgap remains substantial, suggesting that neither the acoustic\n764\tbaseline nor the SSL prosody features capture the perceptual\n765\tdimensions of intonation that human raters rely on.\n766\tWord accent: The best-performing word accent model\n767\tcombines multiple rhythm and intonation methods, achieving\n768\tr = 42.2, which is not significantly different from the human\n769\tscores of r = 47.3 (Figure 5). Shapley decomposition shows\n770\tDTWnorm. res as the largest contributor (39.3%), followed by\n771\ttempo irregularity (denoted TI, 27.7%), with measures targeting\n772\trhythm and intonation each accounting for half of the explained\n773\tvariance. This is consistent with lexical accent in English, where\n774\ta combination of vowel elongation (affecting rhythm) and pitch\n775\tinflection (affecting intonation) is used to stress syllables.\n776\tB. JRF (Japanese)\n777\tOverall sentence score: Though DTWSSL exceeds human\n778\tagreement, the most effective method for holistic scoring of\n779\tJapanese sentences ensembles residual features and DTWSSL ,\n780\tsignificantly exceeding human agreement (r = 66.0 vs.\n781\tr = 60.4). Within this framework, DTWnorm. res is the most\n782\tpredictive feature, accounting for 48.8% of the explained\n783\tvariance in the Shapley decomposition. The two distances\n784\tare nearly collinear (r = 0.98), but partial correlation analysis\n785\tshows controlling for DTWSSL , DTWnorm. res retains a unique\n786\tsignal (rpartial = 0.19) whereas controlling for DTWnorm. res\n787\tleaves DTWSSL with almost none (rpartial = 0.04). This may\n788\tindicate that human raters evaluate overall pronunciation quality\n789\tthrough a macro-perceptual lens, prioritizing structural prosody\n790\tover localized phone accuracy.\n791\t\n792\tTABLE III\n793\tE VALUATION RESULTS FOR TASKS IN THE JRF [41] DATASET (JAPANESE )\n794\tTask/Method\n795\t\n796\tr (↑)\n797\t\n798\tρ (↑) QWK (↑) MAE (↓)\n799\t\n800\tOverall score (sentence)\n801\tHuman benchmark\n802\t\n803\t60.4\n804\t\n805\t60.6\n806\t\n807\t47.7\n808\t\n809\t0.89\n810\t\n811\t66.0\n812\t64.5\n813\t35.6\n814\t\n815\t65.6\n816\t64.4\n817\t36.2\n818\t\n819\t50.8\n820\t47.5\n821\t11.5\n822\t\n823\t0.68\n824\t0.69\n825\t0.82\n826\t\n827\t47.4\n828\t\n829\t48.5\n830\t\n831\t38.5\n832\t\n833\t0.87\n834\t\n835\tσres + F0 –intensity∗\n836\tσres\n837\tF0 (baseline)\n838\tF0 –intensity (baseline)\n839\t\n840\t41.2\n841\t39.7\n842\t17.3\n843\t13.8\n844\t\n845\t45.8\n846\t43.3\n847\t29.7\n848\t16.7\n849\t\n850\t23.7\n851\t20.9\n852\t0.0\n853\t−0.2\n854\t\n855\t0.81\n856\t0.80\n857\t0.97\n858\t0.96\n859\t\n860\tDifficult sounds (word)\n861\tHuman benchmark\n862\t\n863\t47.8\n864\t\n865\t43.8\n866\t\n867\t32.3\n868\t\n869\t1.35\n870\t\n871\t31.9\n872\t18.9\n873\t\n874\t28.7\n875\t17.6\n876\t\n877\t11.9\n878\t3.0\n879\t\n880\t1.20\n881\t1.22\n882\t\n883\tDTWSSL + DTWnorm. res + σres ∗†\n884\tDTWSSL †\n885\tDTWPPG\n886\tIntonation (sentence)\n887\tHuman benchmark\n888\t\n889\tDTWSSL\n890\tDTWPPG\n891\t\n892\t∗ Ensemble method. Bold: best or statistically equivalent (speaker-cluster\n893\tbootstrap, p > 0.05). † Significantly exceeds the human benchmark (p < 0.05).\n894\t\n895\tIntonation: The raters in this task are explicitly instructed\n896\tto listen to pitch accent, but F0 performs relatively poorly\n897\ton its own. Our best method for this task does not include\n898\tDTWnorm. res as with English; it uses a combination of σres and\n899\tF0 –intensity. Shapley analysis attributes 88.7% of predictive\n900\tpower to σres alone. However, the gap between the ensemble\n901\tand σres as a standalone feature is insignificant. This language\n902\tdifference suggests that the rated criteria in the JRF intonation\n903\ttask may differ substantially from those in the ERJ task (where\n904\tσres performs poorly), though the limited linguistic variety in\n905\tthis subset (only 8 texts) warrants caution.\n906\tDifficult sounds: As with English phonetic scoring of words,\n907\tDTWSSL does not perform as well as the sentence counterpart.\n908\tHowever, this task is particularly difficult, as human raters\n909\tattend to specific parts of the words when rating, effectively\n910\tignoring the rest, whereas the DTW cost encapsulates the entire\n911\tutterance.\n912\tVI. C ONCLUSION\n913\tWe showed that DTW over self-supervised representations\n914\tproves a strong basis for multi-aspect pronunciation assessment.\n915\tIt exceeds human inter-rater agreement at the sentence level\n916\tfor holistic and phonetic scoring. For rhythm, the warping\n917\tpath itself directly reflects the temporal deviations that rhythm\n918\tperception is thought to rely on. To our knowledge, our\n919\tproposed methods for rhythm are the current best for comparative rhythm assessment, approaching human performance.\n920\tIntonation remains the open challenge. Our methods provide a\n921\tmodest signal above acoustic baselines, but fall short of human\n922\tagreement. Neither pitch-based features nor SSL prosodic\n923\tresiduals appear to capture what expert raters are actually\n924\tresponding to. Better disentanglement of prosodic information\n925\tfrom SSL representations is the most pressing direction for\n926\tfuture work, alongside evaluation across more languages.\n927\t\n928\t\fVII. AI-G ENERATED C ONTENT D ISCLOSURE\n929\tGenerative AI was used for final proofreading of this\n930\tmanuscript. It was used for code generation, in particular\n931\tdataset normalization, execution time optimization, and data\n932\tvisualization. All experiments were conceived by the authors\n933\tand all final code was manually reviewed and edited for clarity.\n934\tR EFERENCES\n935\t[1] M. Lounis, B. Dendani, and H. Bahi, “Mispronunciation detection and\n936\tdiagnosis using deep neural networks: a systematic review,” Multimedia\n937\tTools and Applications, 2024.\n938\t[2] A. Cutler, D. Dahan, and W. Van Donselaar, “Prosody in the comprehension of spoken language: A literature review,” Language and speech,\n939\t1997.\n94