ion fold in which its speaker was held out. We pool\nTemplate ablation reveals a consistent picture: for the bestthese out-of-fold predictions and compare them to the scores\nperforming method in each task, ≤5 native templates recover\nof each human rater separately, computing all four metrics per\n≥95% of the full-template agreement. Only 2 are required\nrater and then averaging across raters. To contextualize these\nfor English phonetic scoring and Japanese intonation. The\nnumbers, we compute a human benchmark the same way, but\nsole exception is the JRF difficult-sounds task, which requires\ncomparing raters to each other instead of to the model: for\n8. However, the relative rankings of scoring methods remain\nevery pair of raters, we compute the four metrics between their\nstable regardless of the number of templates used.\nscores and then average over all pairs. We assess statistical\nsignificance with a paired speaker-cluster bootstrap on r using\nWe now examine each task in turn, with full per-method\n10,000 resamples.\nbreakdowns in Tables II and III.\nTo understand which features drive ensemble performance,\nwe also apply a Shapley-based attribution framework to each\nensemble model [42]. Shapley values decompose the model’s\nTABLE II\nexplained variance additively across input features, providing\nE VALUATION RESULTS FOR TASKS IN THE ERJ [40] DATASET (E NGLISH )\na principled measure of each feature’s marginal contribution.\nV. R ESULTS\nWe first look at the overall best results before turning to\na detailed analysis. For all assessed tasks, our DTW-based\nmethods comfortably outperform the baselines and largely\napproach human agreement.\nEvaluation results for the best method on each task are\nsummarized in Figure 5. SSL-based methods perform well\noverall, most strikingly for phonetic scoring of sentences,\nwhere DTW over SSL features significantly exceeds human\ninter-rater agreement. Phonetic scoring of isolated words is\nweaker, consistent with the reduced averaging and alignment\nconstraints that short sequences impose on DTW-based methods.\nFor tasks with a rhythmic component (i.e., English sentence\nrhythm and English word accent), our methods fall only slightly\n\nERJ (English)\n\nr (↑)\n\nρ (↑) QWK (↑) MAE (↓)\n\nPhones (sentence)\nHuman benchmark\n\n53.6\n\n51.5\n\n49.1\n\n0.75\n\n57.6\n36.9\n\n55.8\n36.5\n\n44.7\n18.3\n\n0.64\n0.72\n\n49.3\n\n48.2\n\n45.9\n\n0.81\n\n44.9\n43.6\n43.5\n37.3\n31.7\n16.5\n\n45.8\n44.9\n44.2\n39.0\n30.3\n16.5\n\n33.8\n31.3\n32.4\n25.9\n21.8\n10.2\n\n0.73\n0.74\n0.73\n0.76\n0.78\n0.84\n\n45.3\n\n44.8\n\n38.6\n\n0.98\n\n32.9\n21.9\n18.7\n16.9\n\n32.5\n21.0\n18.6\n18.3\n\n15.5\n2.5\n3.9\n0.9\n\n0.87\n0.89\n0.89\n0.90\n\n72.1\n\n72.0\n\n71.3\n\n0.60\n\n61.4\n37.6\n\n64.0\n38.7\n\n51.7\n24.4\n\n0.70\n0.85\n\n47.3\n\n41.5\n\n35.0\n\n0.95\n\n42.2\n20.2\n0.3\n−2.9\n\n41.4\n21.6\n−3.9\n−3.4\n\n23.9\n4.4\n0.0\n0.0\n\n0.76\n0.80\n0.81\n0.81\n\nDTWSSL †\nDTWPPG\nRhythm (sentence)\nHuman benchmark\nRdur + Interval distortion∗\nInterval distortion\nRdur + Tempo irregularity∗\nTempo irregularity\nRdur (baseline)\nnPVIV (baseline)\nIntonation (sentence)\nHuman benchmark\nL6\n∗\nDTWL6\nnorm. res + σres + F0 –intensity\nF0 –intensity (baseline)\nσres\nF0 (baseline)\n\nPhones sentence\nRhythm sentence\nIntonation sentence\nPhones word\nAccent word\n\nPhones (word)\nHuman benchmark\n\nJRF (Japanese)\n\nOverall sentence\nIntonation sentence\nDifficult sounds word\n0\n\nTask/Method\n\nDTWSSL\nDTWPPG\nAccent (word)\nHuman benchmark\n\n20\n\n40\n60\nPearson's r\n\n80\n\nFig. 5. Best model vs. the human benchmark on each task. Dots are blue when\nthe model exceeds human agreement and red otherwise. Whiskers show the\n95% confidence interval of model − human; a whisker clear of the benchmark\ntick indicates a statistically significant difference.\n\nRdur + TI + σres + DTWnorm. res ∗\nRdur (baseline)\nF0 (baseline)\nF0 –intensity (baseline)\n\n∗ Ensemble method. Bold: best or statistically equivalent (speaker-cluster\nbootstrap, p > 0.05). † Significantly exceeds the human benchmark (p < 0.05).\n\n\fA. ERJ (English)\nPhones: For phonetic scoring of sentences, standard DTW\ndistance on SSL features (r = 57.6) alone significantly exceeds\nhuman agreement (r = 53.6). However, the results are worse\nfor the phonetic scoring of words, which is understandable, as\nSSL models rely on context in a longer utterance to improve\nthe quality of representations.\nSentence rhythm: The best-performing rhythm model\ncombines Rdur and interval distortion (r = 44.9, the highest\namong suprasegmental tasks), though interval distortion alone\n(r = 43.6) is statistically indistinguishable from it. These are\nclose because interval distortion already encodes speech rate\n(Pearson correlation is 0.44 with Rdur ), so the inclusion of\nduration does not contribute much (28.8% of the ensemble’s\nexplained variance). In contrast, tempo irregularity is nearly\nrate-invariant (0.24 correlation with Rdur ), so it benefits more\nfrom ensembling with duration (which is responsible for 40.3%\nof the explained variance). All of the best methods incorporate\nboth global speaking rate and local timing information, consistent with findings that more proficient speakers speak more\nquickly and have more appropriate local rhythm [43].\nIntonation: Our best-performing intonation method achieves\nr = 32.9 (human benchmark r = 45.3), among the lowest of all\nevaluated tasks. Shapley attribution indicates that DTWL6\nnorm. res\nis the dominant contributor (41.0%), followed by F0 –intensity\nL6\nfeatures (31.2%) and σres\n(27.8%). Despite achieving a lower\nMAE than the human benchmark (0.87 vs. 0.98), the correlation\ngap remains substantial, suggesting that neither the acoustic\nbaseline nor the SSL prosody features capture the perceptual\ndimensions of intonation that human raters rely on.\nWord accent: The best-performing word accent model\ncombines multiple rhythm and intonation methods, achieving\nr = 42.2, which is not significantly different from the human\nscores of r = 47.3 (Figure 5). Shapley decomposition shows\nDTWnorm. res as the largest contributor (39.3%), followed by\ntempo irregularity (denoted TI, 27.7%), with measures targeting\nrhythm and intonation each accounting for half of the explained\nvariance. This is consistent with lexical accent in English, where\na combination of vowel elongation (affecting rhythm) and pitch\ninflection (affecting intonation) is used to stress syllables.\nB. JRF (Japanese)\nOverall sentence score: Though DTWSSL exceeds human\nagreement, the most effective method for holistic scoring of\nJapanese sentences ensembles residual features and DTWSSL ,\nsignificantly exceeding human agreement (r = 66.0 vs.\nr = 60.4). Within this framework, DTWnorm. res is the most\npredictive feature, accounting for 48.8% of the explained\nvariance in the Shapley decomposition. The two distances\nare nearly collinear (r = 0.98), but partial correlation analysis\nshows controlling for DTWSSL , DTWnorm. res retains a unique\nsignal (rpartial = 0.19) whereas controlling for DTWnorm. res\nleaves DTWSSL with almost none (rpartial = 0.04). This may\nindicate that human raters evaluate overall pronunciation quality\nthrough a macro-perceptual lens, prioritizing structural prosody\nover localized phone accuracy.\n\nTABLE III\nE VALUATION RESULTS FOR TASKS IN THE JRF [41] DATASET (JAPANESE )\nTask/Method\n\nr (↑)\n\nρ (↑) QWK (↑) MAE (↓)\n\nOverall score (sentence)\nHuman benchmark\n\n60.4\n\n60.6\n\n47.7\n\n0.89\n\n66.0\n64.5\n35.6\n\n65.6\n64.4\n36.2\n\n50.8\n47.5\n11.5\n\n0.68\n0.69\n0.82\n\n47.4\n\n48.5\n\n38.5\n\n0.87\n\nσres + F0 –intensity∗\nσres\nF0 (baseline)\nF0 –intensity (baseline)\n\n41.2\n39.7\n17.3\n13.8\n\n45.8\n43.3\n29.7\n16.7\n\n23.7\n20.9\n0.0\n−0.2\n\n0.81\n0.80\n0.97\n0.96\n\nDifficult sounds (word)\nHuman benchmark\n\n47.8\n\n43.8\n\n32.3\n\n1.35\n\n31.9\n18.9\n\n28.7\n17.6\n\n11.9\n3.0\n\n1.20\n1.22\n\nDTWSSL + DTWnorm. res + σres ∗†\nDTWSSL †\nDTWPPG\nIntonation (sentence)\nHuman benchmark\n\nDTWSSL\nDTWPPG\n\n∗ Ensemble method. Bold: best or statistically equivalent (speaker-cluster\nbootstrap, p > 0.05). † Significantly exceeds the human benchmark (p < 0.05).\n\nIntonation: The raters in this task are explicitly instructed\nto listen to pitch accent, but F0 performs relatively poorly\non its own. Our best method for this task does not include\nDTWnorm. res as with English; it uses a combination of σres and\nF0 –intensity. Shapley analysis attributes 88.7% of predictive\npower to σres alone. However, the gap between the ensemble\nand σres as a standalone feature is insignificant. This language\ndifference suggests that the rated criteria in the JRF intonation\ntask may differ substantially from those in the ERJ task (where\nσres performs poorly), though the limited linguistic variety in\nthis subset (only 8 texts) warrants caution.\nDifficult sounds: As with English phonetic scoring of words,\nDTWSSL does not perform as well as the sentence counterpart.\nHowever, this task is particularly difficult, as human raters\nattend to specific parts of the words when rating, effectively\nignoring the rest, whereas the DTW cost encapsulates the entire\nutterance.\nVI. C ONCLUSION\nWe showed that DTW over self-supervised representations\nproves a strong basis for multi-aspect pronunciation assessment.\nIt exceeds human inter-rater agreement at the sentence level\nfor holistic and phonetic scoring. For rhythm, the warping\npath itself directly reflects the temporal deviations that rhythm\nperception is thought to rely on. To our knowledge, our\nproposed methods for rhythm are the current best for comparative rhythm assessment, approaching human performance.\nIntonation remains the open challenge. Our methods provide a\nmodest signal above acoustic baselines, but fall short of human\nagreement. Neither pitch-based features nor SSL prosodic\nresiduals appear to capture what expert raters are actually\nresponding to. Better disentanglement of prosodic information\nfrom SSL representations is the most pressing direction for\nfuture work, alongside evaluation across more languages.\n\n\fVII. AI-G ENERATED C ONTENT D ISCLOSURE\nGenerative AI was used for final proofreading of this\nmanuscript. It was used for code generation, in particular\ndataset normalization, execution time optimization, and data\nvisualization. All experiments were conceived by the authors\nand all final code was manually reviewed and edited for clarity.\nR EFERENCES\n[1] M. Lounis, B. Dendani, and H. Bahi, “Mispronunciation detection and\ndiagnosis using deep neural networks: a systematic review,” Multimedia\nTools and Applications, 2024.\n[2] A. Cutler, D. Dahan, and W. Van Donselaar, “Prosody in the comprehension of spoken language: A literature review,” Language and speech,\n1997.\n[3] D. Dahan, “Prosody and language comprehension,” Wiley Interdisciplinary Reviews: Cognitive Science, 2015.\n[4] R. Bae, “The effects of pausing on comprehensibility,” Master’s thesis,\nIowa State University, 2015.\n[5] K. Tajima, R. Port, and J. Dalby, “Effects of temporal correction on\nintelligibility of foreign-accented English,” Journal of Phonetics, 1997.\n[6] T. M. Derwing, M. J. Munro, and G. Wiebe, “Evidence in favor of\na broad framework for pronunciation instruction,” Language learning,\n1998.\n[7] L. Van Maastricht, T. Zee, E. Krahmer, and M. Swerts, “The interplay\nof prosodic cues in the L2: How intonation, rhythm, and speech rate in\nspeech by spanish learners of Dutch contribute to L1 Dutch perceptions\nof accentedness and comprehensibility,” Speech Communication, 2021.\n[8] S. M. Witt and S. J. Young, “Phone-level pronunciation scoring and\nassessment for interactive language learning,” Speech Communication,\n2000.\n[9] H. Strik, K. Truong, F. De Wet, and C. Cucchiarini, “Comparing\ndifferent approaches for automatic pronunciation error detection,” Speech\nCommunication, 2009.\n[10] W. Hu, Y. Qian, and F. K. Soong, “A new DNN-based high quality\npronunciation evaluation for computer-aided language learning (CALL).”\nin Interspeech, 2013.\n[11] J. Shi, N. Huo, and Q. Jin, “Context-aware goodness of pronunciation\nfor computer-assisted pronunciation training,” in Interspeech, 2020.\n[12] B.-C. Yan, M.-C. Wu, H.-T. Hung, and B. Chen, “An end-to-end\nmispronunciation detection system for L2 English speech leveraging\nnovel anti-phone modeling,” in Interspeech, 2020.\n[13] Y. Gong, Z. Chen, I.-H. Chu, P. Chang, and J. Glass, “Transformer-based\nmulti-aspect multi-granularity non-native english speaker pronunciation\nassessment,” in ICASSP, 2022.\n[14] A. Lee and J. Glass, “A comparison-based approach to mispronunciation\ndetection,” in SLT, 2012.\n[15] M. Bartelds, C. Richter, M. Liberman, and M. Wieling, “A new acousticbased pronunciation distance measure,” Frontiers in Artificial Intelligence,\n2020.\n[16] A. Lee and J. Glass, “Pronunciation assessment via a comparison-based\nsystem,” in SLaTE, 2013.\n[17] A. Lee, Y. Zhang, and J. Glass, “Mispronunciation detection via dynamic\ntime warping on deep belief network-based posteriorgrams,” in ICASSP,\n2013.\n[18] T. J. Hazen, W. Shen, and C. White, “Query-by-example spoken term\ndetection using phonetic posteriorgram templates,” in ASRU, 2009.\n[19] A. Baevski, Y. Zhou, A. Mohamed, and M. Auli, “wav2vec 2.0:\nA framework for self-supervised learning of speech representations,”\nNeurIPS, 2020.\n[20] W.-N. Hsu, B. Bolte, Y.-H. H. Tsai, K. Lakhotia, R. Salakhutdinov, and\nA. Mohamed, “HuBERT: Self-supervised speech representation learning\nby masked prediction of hidden units,” Transactions on audio, speech,\nand language processing, 2021.\n[21] M. Bartelds, W. de Vries, F. Sanal, C. Richter, M. Liberman, and\nM. Wieling, “Neural representations for modeling variation in speech,”\nJournal of Phonetics, 2022.\n[22] A. de la Fuente and D. Jurafsky, “A layer-wise analysis of mandarin and\nenglish suprasegmentals in ssl speech models,” in Interspeech, 2024.\n[23] H. Sun, S. McIntosh, K. Choi, E. Yeo, D. Saito, and N. Minematsu,\n“Prosodic ABX: A language-agnostic method for measuring prosodic\ncontrast in speech representations,” arXiv preprint arXiv:2604.02102,\n2026.\n\n[24] S. Chen, C. Wang, Z. Chen, Y. Wu, S. Liu, Z. Chen, J. Li, N. Kanda,\nT. Yoshioka, X. Xiao et al., “WavLM: Large-scale self-supervised pretraining for full stack speech processing,” Journal of Selected Topics in\nSignal Processing, 2022.\n[25] C. Churchwell, M. Morrison, and B. Pardo, “High-fidelity neural phonetic\nposteriorgrams,” in ICASSP, 2024.\n[26] K. L. Pike, The Intonation of American English. ERIC, 1945.\n[27] D. Abercrombie, Elements of general phonetics. Aldine, Chicago, 1967.\n[28] R. M. Dauer, “Stress-timing and syllable-timing reanalyzed,” Journal of\nphonetics, 1983.\n[29] F. Ramus, M. Nespor, and J. Mehler, “Correlates of linguistic rhythm in\nthe speech signal,” Cognition, 1999.\n[30] F. Ramus, “Acoustic correlates of linguistic rhythm: Perspectives,” in\nSpeech Prosody, 2002.\n[31] J. S. Garofolo, L. F. Lamel, W. M. Fisher, D. S. Pallett, N. L. Dahlgren,\nV. Zue, and J. G. Fiscus, “TIMIT acoustic-phonetic continuous speech\ncorpus,” 1993.\n[32] E. Grabe and E. L. Low, “Durational variability in speech and the rhythm\nclass hypothesis,” Laboratory Phonology, 2002.\n[33] K. Tajima and R. F. Port, “Speech rhythm in english and japanese,”\nin Phonetic Interpretation: Papers in Laboratory Phonology VI, ser.\nPapers in Laboratory Phonology, J. Local, R. Ogden, and R. Temple,\nEds. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 2004, pp. 322–339.\n[34] Y. Sim, J. Yoon, W. Jeong, and Y.-J. Suh, “QR-VC: Leveraging\nquantization residuals for linear disentanglement in zero-shot voice\nconversion,” in EUSIPCO, 2025.\n[35] R. Aihara, Y. Masuyama, F. G. Germain, G. Wichern, and J. L. Roux,\n“Exploring disentangled neural speech codecs from self-supervised\nrepresentations,” in ICASSP, 2026.\n[36] V. Panayotov, G. Chen, D. Povey, and S. Khudanpur, “LibriSpeech: an\nASR corpus based on public domain audio books,” in ICASSP, 2015.\n[37] M. Baas, B. van Niekerk, and H. Kamper, “Voice conversion with just\nnearest neighbors,” in Interspeech, 2023.\n[38] H. Kamper, B. van Niekerk, J. Zaı̈di, and M.-A. Carbonneau, “LinearVC:\nLinear transformations of self-supervised features through the lens of\nvoice conversion,” in Interspeech, 2025.\n[39] M. Morrison, “torchcrepe: A pytorch implementation of crepe,”\nhttps://github.com/maxrmorrison/torchcrepe, 2020.\n[40] S. Nakagawa, “UME English Speech Database Read by Japanese\nStudents (UME-ERJ),” Speech Resources Consortium (SRC), 2007.\n[Online]. Available: https://doi.org/10.32130/src.UME-ERJ\n[41] ——, “UME Japanese Speech Database Read by Foreign Students\n(UME-JRF),” Speech Resources Consortium (SRC), 2007. [Online].\nAvailable: https://doi.org/10.32130/src.UME-JRF\n[42] S. M. Lundberg and S.-I. Lee, “A unified approach to interpreting model\npredictions,” NeurIPS, 2017.\n[43] E. Galaczi, B. Post, A. Li, F. Barker, and E. Schmidt, “Assessing second\nlanguage pronunciation: Distinguishing features of rhythm in learner\nspeech at different proficiency levels,” Second Language Pronunciation\nAssessment, 2017.\n\n\f", "numLines": 1047, "startLine": 1, "totalLines": 1047}}}
